00:15:57.750 --> 00:15:59.740 align:middle line:90%
alcohol all suppress alpha.

00:15:59.740 --> 00:16:01.740 align:middle line:90%
They do it in different ways.

00:16:01.740 --> 00:16:04.771 align:middle line:84%
Caffeine is a
vasoconstrictor, reduces

00:16:04.771 --> 00:16:05.770 align:middle line:90%
blood flow to the brain.

00:16:05.770 --> 00:16:08.140 align:middle line:90%
Same with nicotine.

00:16:08.140 --> 00:16:11.080 align:middle line:84%
If somebody-- one
time we had a lady

00:16:11.080 --> 00:16:13.187 align:middle line:84%
who interrupted her
alpha training session,

00:16:13.187 --> 00:16:14.645 align:middle line:84%
said she had to go
to the bathroom,

00:16:14.645 --> 00:16:16.779 align:middle line:84%
but curiously she
took her purse along.

00:16:16.779 --> 00:16:18.320 align:middle line:84%
When she came back
from the bathroom,

00:16:18.320 --> 00:16:20.820 align:middle line:90%
she smelled like tobacco smoke.

00:16:20.820 --> 00:16:22.590 align:middle line:84%
When she sat down
in the chamber,

00:16:22.590 --> 00:16:25.410 align:middle line:84%
the alpha that she had
just before leaving

00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:29.640 align:middle line:84%
was reduced by a
factor of about five.

00:16:29.640 --> 00:16:30.750 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Interesting

00:16:30.750 --> 00:16:32.810 align:middle line:84%
>>HARDT: And it
was just amazing.

00:16:32.810 --> 00:16:35.440 align:middle line:84%
Nicotine, because it
goes through the lungs

00:16:35.440 --> 00:16:37.792 align:middle line:84%
when you smoke, goes
right to the bloodstream.

00:16:37.792 --> 00:16:39.500 align:middle line:84%
Caffeine, which goes
through the stomach,

00:16:39.500 --> 00:16:41.864 align:middle line:90%
takes a little bit longer.

00:16:41.864 --> 00:16:43.530 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So these
are vasoconstrictors.

00:16:43.530 --> 00:16:45.500 align:middle line:84%
And so yet in the
morning, people

00:16:45.500 --> 00:16:46.991 align:middle line:84%
feel like, I just
can't get going

00:16:46.991 --> 00:16:49.490 align:middle line:84%
until I have my cup of coffee
and in some cases a cigarette.

00:16:49.490 --> 00:16:50.530 align:middle line:90%
But what's going on there?

00:16:50.530 --> 00:16:52.863 align:middle line:84%
>>HARDT: Well, most people
have chronically under-slept.

00:16:52.863 --> 00:16:56.040 align:middle line:84%
And so when they wake
up, they're still groggy.

00:16:56.040 --> 00:16:57.830 align:middle line:84%
Instead of waking
up naturally, they

00:16:57.830 --> 00:17:01.550 align:middle line:84%
were probably dragged from
delta by their alarm clock,

00:17:01.550 --> 00:17:02.624 align:middle line:90%
straight into beta.

00:17:02.624 --> 00:17:04.540 align:middle line:84%
And so they feel stressed,
and they're groggy,

00:17:04.540 --> 00:17:05.915 align:middle line:84%
and they didn't
get enough sleep.

00:17:05.915 --> 00:17:09.163 align:middle line:84%
And so they put in way too
much caffeine or nicotine

00:17:09.163 --> 00:17:10.079 align:middle line:90%
to wake themselves up.

00:17:10.079 --> 00:17:12.204 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So it's like--
it's having a dual effect.

00:17:12.204 --> 00:17:15.329 align:middle line:84%
On one level, it's boosting
dopamine in the body.

00:17:15.329 --> 00:17:17.520 align:middle line:84%
But on another, it's
restricting the-- as

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:20.175 align:middle line:90%
you say-- the vassal function.

00:17:20.175 --> 00:17:21.550 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well,
and alcohol works

00:17:21.550 --> 00:17:23.780 align:middle line:84%
in a little bit of
a different way.

00:17:23.780 --> 00:17:25.790 align:middle line:84%
Most people know
about happy hour.

00:17:25.790 --> 00:17:27.930 align:middle line:84%
So they have high stress
work, they get off work,

00:17:27.930 --> 00:17:29.980 align:middle line:84%
they go to a bar, and
they start drinking.

00:17:29.980 --> 00:17:33.560 align:middle line:84%
And so alcohol relaxes
them physically.

00:17:33.560 --> 00:17:36.870 align:middle line:84%
And so there may actually be
a period of about 45 minutes

00:17:36.870 --> 00:17:38.370 align:middle line:84%
where their alpha
actually goes up,

00:17:38.370 --> 00:17:40.440 align:middle line:84%
because they're letting
go of the stress

00:17:40.440 --> 00:17:43.070 align:middle line:84%
and the tension in their
muscles is relaxing.

00:17:43.070 --> 00:17:48.030 align:middle line:84%
However, alcohol is a central
nervous system depressant.

00:17:48.030 --> 00:17:51.240 align:middle line:84%
And so if somebody
had even one beer,

00:17:51.240 --> 00:17:53.199 align:middle line:84%
I can measure 24
hours later they're

00:17:53.199 --> 00:17:54.990 align:middle line:84%
going to have less
alpha in their baselines

00:17:54.990 --> 00:17:58.110 align:middle line:84%
than if they hadn't
had that one beer.

00:17:58.110 --> 00:18:01.490 align:middle line:84%
And so all of these
things suppress alpha.

00:18:01.490 --> 00:18:04.450 align:middle line:84%
Now, if you're talking
about onions and garlic,

00:18:04.450 --> 00:18:06.759 align:middle line:90%
I was raised in a German family.

00:18:06.759 --> 00:18:08.300 align:middle line:84%
And although we used
a lot of onions,

00:18:08.300 --> 00:18:10.229 align:middle line:90%
garlic wasn't a part of it.

00:18:10.229 --> 00:18:12.520 align:middle line:84%
Garlic wasn't really part of
American culture very much

00:18:12.520 --> 00:18:14.280 align:middle line:90%
until maybe 30 years ago.

00:18:14.280 --> 00:18:16.280 align:middle line:90%
And then it spread more broadly.

